==== Statistics

We utilized tree-sitter @tree-sitter, a fast parsing library that constructs Abstract Syntax Trees (AST), to evaluate the output's syntactic correctness, allowing us to confirm whether the generated bridge code formed valid Rust syntax when integrated back into the larger file.

We measured Levenshtein distance between the output and ground truth, and computed the average edit ratio. Formula of Levenshtein edit ratio $R$ is as follows, with the size of test dataset $n$, a dataset row's prefix length $p_i$, suffix length $s_i$, model output length $m_i$, and Levenshtein editing distance $l_i$:

$
  R = 1/n sum_(i=1)^n l_i/(p_i + m_i + s_i)
$

We used the Hugging Face's `evaluate` library to calculate BLEU scores on the isolated generated snippets, which strictly measured n-gram string overlap against the ground truth. The results are shown in @results. As the data shows, we yield significantly better syntactic correctness

