== Discussion and Limitations

=== Data Quality

The training dataset includes pre-alpha Rust code from as early as 2012, predating the stable 1.0 release in 2015. Because these snippets use deprecated, invalid syntax (as reflected by the ground-truth syntactic correctness results), the finetuned model also learned archaic patterns, limiting its ability to produce consistently correct, modern Rust code.

=== Vulnerability to Prompt Injection

We also identified a structural limitation in how the FIM templates are processed. Since code snippets are not sanitized or escaped, any raw text containing the control strings used for formatting (such as `<fim_middle>`) can accidentally act as a prompt injection, disrupting parsing and causing the model to start or stop generation at unintended positions rather than at the true prompt boundaries.

=== Semantic Correctness

While the finetuned model achieved high syntactic correctness, structural validity does not guarantee executable logic. Because the dataset consists of isolated snippets lacking full repository context, we could not test the generated code against the Rust compiler. Consequently, we were unable to evaluate the model's adherence to Rust’s strict semantic paradigms, such as borrow checking, variable mutability, and lifetime management.

These tasks are not conducted in this mini-project and remain future work.

== Conclusion


This project successfully demonstrated that OFT can efficiently adapt a 1.5B Small Language Model for specialized FIM code completion. The finetuned model significantly outperformed the base model in syntactic correctness, BLEU, and CodeBLEU metrics, proving finetuning improvements. Despite minor limitations caused by dataset noise and model capacity, the results validate OFT as a highly resource-efficient method for building domain-specific development tools.

